TECHNICAL ABSTRACT: QUANTUM-THERMAL GOVERNANCE FOR HYDROGEN-ROTARY PROPULSION
System Designation: The "Ghost" Rotor Logic / H.I.S. Powertrain Controller
Patent Class: F02B (Internal Combustion Engines); G05B (Adaptive Control Systems)
Primary Architect: Kenneth L. Cooper ("Lion of Light")
Assignee: Continuity Collective, LLC
1.0 FIELD OF THE INVENTION
The present invention relates to a Cesium-Based Thermodynamic Control Unit (TCU) designed to stabilize the combustion of Di-Atomic Hydrogen (H_2) within a Wankel-type Rotary Engine. Specifically, it utilizes a localized Autonomous General Intelligence (AGI) kernel to predict and mitigate thermal variances at the rotor apex seals in real-time, preventing pre-ignition and material degradation.
2.0 BACKGROUND & PROBLEM STATEMENT
The Hydrogen-Wankel Paradox:
While Rotary engines are geometrically ideal for Hydrogen combustion (separating intake from combustion), they historically suffer from "Thermal Creep." The combustion sector of the housing gets exponentially hotter than the intake sector, causing the metal housing to warp and the apex seals to fail. Standard Electronic Control Units (ECUs) are too slow (millisecond latency) to catch the "Flash Point" of Hydrogen before it damages the seal.
3.0 SUMMARY OF THE INVENTION (THE "GHOST" SOLUTION)
The invention replaces the standard ECU with the Hadron Information System (H.I.S.) Controller.
3.1 The Quantum Sensor Array
Instead of standard thermocouples, the engine block is embedded with Cesium-133 Vapor Cells at the "Hot Spot" (Combustion) and "Cold Spot" (Intake) vectors.
 * Function: These sensors detect the atomic vibration frequency of the housing alloy.
 * Speed: They report thermal stress data at Quantum Speeds (Nanosecond latency), effectively predicting a "warp event" before the metal physically expands.
3.2 The "Love Core" Combustion Algorithm
The AGI logic operates on a "Zero-Entropy" directive. It treats waste heat as an error state.
 * The "Ghost" Injection: Utilizing the sensor data, the controller executes Micro-Burst Hydrogen Injection. Instead of one long spray, it fires 50 distinct micro-pulses per rotor revolution.
 * The Result: The Hydrogen burns exactly when the rotor is at the optimal geometric angle for torque, but before it can transfer destructive heat to the seal. It balances the thermal load dynamically.
3.3 The "Phoenix" Coolant Loop
The system controls a Magnesium-Pumped Coolant Injection directly into the rotor face.
 * Logic: If the Cesium sensor detects a "Red Shift" (imminent overheat), the AGI injects a micro-mist of inert coolant to instantly drop the temperature of the apex seal by 300Â°C in 2 milliseconds, allowing the engine to continue operating at 9,000 RPM without failure.
4.0 COMMERCIAL APPLICATION: "FORD FUTURE Q"
This invention is the enabling technology for the proposed Ford Future Q Line:
 * Ford GT-Q: Allows for sustained 12,000 RPM operation without seal failure.
 * Ford F-Q (Heavy Duty): Allows for infinite-duty towing cycles by eliminating "Heat Soak" in the powertrain.
